Cruise Line Suggestion For Me?

Hey all,

 

I'm looking to do a cruise with my girlfriend, and don't have a local travel agency to consult with, so I'm hoping ya'll can give me some tips on selecting a cruise line.

 

I've only been on two cruises, the girlfriend three. For me, all two cruises were on MSC on the Divina within the Yacht Club. I hope if I tell you what i liked and what i didn't, it can help guide me to a choice for my next cruise. Apologize in advanced for the massive wall of text to follow.

 

Here's what I liked most:
1. The food. (ate dinner every night at Le Muse, the yacht club restaurant. The idea of not needing a reservation, or to pay more, and being able to order whatever I wanted, was great. I tried all sorts of food I normally wouldn't eat, because they had no problem providing multiple courses at no additional expense. The experience of eating at that restaurant was great too, which I'll bring up next.)
2. The personalized experience from the staff. Every employee within the Yacht Club knew me, if not by name, within a day. Bartenders knew my preferences, etc. Everyone made me feel better than being at home.
3. The semi-private spaces for Yacht-Club cruisers. The private pool deck and pool bar, plus lounge, was honestly where we spent most of our time. No location within the Yacht Club area ever felt crowded at all, and all the guests in the area were pleasant to interact with, we made friends on both cruises there. I really loved the fact there was someone playing the grand piano in the lounge every night, though sometimes i felt like they weren't there long enough. I could spend most of the night there relaxing.
4. The drinks package, and how it worked while in the Yacht Club. Having unlimited alcoholic drinks is a huge plus for me, because if i'm on vacation I can really suck down the whiskey at night, and the pina coladas in the day. The best part was while in the yacht club area, there was no need to provide the cruise card to prove you had the drinks package, because they all knew if you were in that area, it was included.
5. How those other things combined provided an almost all-inclusive experience where I basically didn't need to pay any extra than my cruise fare, and everything I wanted on a regular basis was close to my cabin.

 

What I didn't like:
1. Everything outside of the Yacht club was a complete and utter mess. Overcrowding everywhere. It was almost impossible to get a drink at any bar other than the ones in the yacht club, because they were so full, and you had to hold up your cruise card and waive it around for a bartender to even notice you most of the time. The only exceptions here being when we were in a port during the day and most of the other cruisers were off the ship.
2. An egregious amount of attempts to nickle and dime me. While I loved most of the service received, including the amazing butler and room service, I was shocked at how expensive excursions were, and that even when I paid top dollar to be part of the yacht club, I still needed to pay extra for the other dining and various activities. (And laundry!) I understand this is pretty common in the industry, but it was still a bit of a shock to me. Especially the automatic tipping applied automatically at the end of the trip. I'd greatly prefer something in the future to have as much included in the base fare as possible.

 

Besides that, it should be noted that the majority of the time we spent on the ship, either in our cabin on the balcony, or in the private yacht club areas. We would disembark for maybe an hour or two at the ports to check things out on our own, but always headed back rather quickly. We both preferred sitting on our balcony, sipping a drink, and looking at the port from afar, to exploring the port. Even better, chilling in the almost private yacht club only pool with just a couple other cruisers, looking out at the port.
Outside of the entertainment in the Yacht Club lounge, we didn't bother going to any shows, nor did we gamble or do any of the other activities. (I may have done some of the bowling if it was included...)
Similarly, the dates and destinations of the cruise are of very low importance. Its about having a mostly all-inclusive experience on the boat, and having regularly changing scenery. I'd prefer a trip to be around 14 days, but could go over or under by a few. Like many others, one of my concerns is getting good bang for my buck in terms of price per night.
While I don't mind flying somewhere to board a cruise, I would greatly prefer round-trip from a US port so I can drive to the port first. I hate airline travel, and the girlfriend always over-packs, so I can always over-stuff my car with luggage without paying more. I've got plenty of hotel loyalty points i can redeem for free night stays, so, even if the drive is to the other end of the country, its still probably cheaper than flying, too.

 

Lastly, and, unfortunately, there was an issue on my last MSC cruise that their customer service completely failed to correct. I find this unacceptable, and why I'm looking on guidance for a different cruise line. Otherwise, I probably would have been happy to continue cruising on their ships.

 

So, based on that, I've been trying to figure out where I should go next. Everyone raves about Oceania's food, so since that was easily my favorite part of the cruise, i looked there first. They seem OK, but a more luxury oriented company charging higher rates already that doesn't include everything put me off a bit, which brought me to Azamara, which is currently probably the top contender. I'm also thinking about doing an NCL Haven or Celebrity Retreat cruise, but they seem to be more expensive for a shorter duration than Azamara and even some of the other smaller more luxury lines. Since i didn't really do any of the big-boat stuff on MSC, I was thinking one of the lines with smaller ships might make the most sense, especially if they are cheaper. However, if NCL or Celebrity's Haven or Retreat are comparable - and the rest of their ship isn't such a calamity, I could definitely see doing them instead.

Just because I mentioned those four lines doesn't mean i'm not open to something else. I was really considering WindStar just because the idea of being on a sailboat is neat.

 

So, can anyone help guide me?

I hate to tell you this, but based on the experience of others who travel in the Retreat on Celebrity, the Haven on NCL or whatever Royal has, you are not going to get the same level of food and service that you get in the YC without paying considerably more.  And you wouldnt get the same exclusivity.  What you want you can find for much more on the luxury lines, and in the Grills class on Cunard, but again for much more.  I have traveled. SC, but not in the YC, and have enjoyed it.  Especially since I can drive to Port Canaveral.  You might go to the MDC board here and read some of the live threads, most of which seem to be in the YC.  And pose your question therewhat compares.  EM

Posted November 15, 2024
  On 11/15/2024 at 4:52 PM, MachoDogDandyRavage said:

 

Sure have. They seem to be priced higher for a similar experience than Azamara, without including a drinks package. Though, they do offer inclusive airfare to some cruisings, which could offset the difference depending on the destination. I'd love it if people on here who had cruised on both could compare them, from the videos i've seen online they seem neck and neck.

 

Viking provides complimentary beer and wine at both lunch and dinner, and they are fairly easy going on pours. No issues taking a full glass with you after the meal.

 

You can also bring aboard any alcoholic beverages (no restrictions on quantity) and they will happily serve your own wines in the dining room (no corkage fees). All specialty teas and coffees are also included.

 

Self-service laundry machines are included, as is the soap liquid.

 

With respect to ships, Azamara's are all the older "R-Class" ships from the turn of the century, while Viking's fleet is all < 10 yrs old. Great decor and they have lots of quiet spaces throughout the ship. Many of the lounges have shelves of books from the ship's library.

 

The spa area is also included in the base price.

@MachoDogDandyRavage:  Thank you for your detailed review and listing of your preferences.  I think what you have said is more helpful to me than what I'm about to say to you.  I've never been on MSC, never mind the Yacht Club, but based on what you and others have said about it, I don't think I'm interested at this point in my life.  I mostly like the peasant food to be had at the trough on most cruise lines I've used, I don't react well to being pampered and called out by name unduly, don't generally need private areas other than my cabin, don't drink at all, and don't mind watching my nickels and dimes on a cruise.  In addition, I don't mind the peasants I've met on my mainstream cruises (most of the time) and value the entertainment on the bigger ships too much to easily give them up.

 

My one piece of advice is to try to find a travel agent that specializes in luxury cruise experiences.  They can give you a better idea of what other cruises you might enjoy, because of either personal experience, extensive cruise line knowledge, or both.  Sadly, discussion of TAs here is sharply limited, so good luck finding one.

 

Good luck with your research and future cruises!

Please feel free to browse the Cruise Critic Community categories list of the various discussion forums. I suggest you put the page link in your browser's Favorites for quick & easy access in the future. Please read a few threads in the different forums to get a feel for what each forum is about. Make sure you read any pinned threads (aka stickies) on the top of the first page of threads in most forums. You will find very important instructions or information there. 

 

In regard to what @Honolulu Blue said above, perhaps something in the following Cruise Critic article will be helpful: Why You Need Luxury Cruise Travel Agents -- and How to Find a Good One Last updated February 5, 2024

We went on an Azamara cruise in Greece.  The food and service were great, and the ship was well maintained, and lovely.  BUT - The shower is quite small, and had a curtain instead of a door.  That curtain can get very clingy.  It may seem like a small thing, but that alone had ruled out future Azamara cruises for us.  Now, we were in a standard balcony, perhaps the suites have more spacious bathrooms.  But that is one of the "old ship" things that people refer to.
